<h1>brian on ...</h1>

     
          <h4>Wednesday, August 21, 2002</h4>
     
     <blockquote>
 		  <a name="80508662"></a><br>
          up on the roof...<br><p>Between heaven and earth are the rooftops of New York.  The city street below is the domaiun of humankind.  It teems with the bustle and hustle, the wheeling and dealing of a city always on the verge of making its own dreams reality.  Its a demanding and sweaty domain that requires everything you can give it.  Above you, the heavens stretch as far as you can believe.  They're never really touched but for brief leaps constrained by steel and glass - yet nothing of our ilk reaches above us.<br><p>But on the roof, you're in neither of those places yet you feel intertwined with both.  Just over the edge you can feel part of that roiling rush of streetlife - the cars and peopel conducting their business as usual.  You can witness the same activities that you yourself engage in every day and night without thought, but on the roof you stand beside yourself witnessing your own act.  At the same time, nothing comes between you and the great beyond, you're as close as you can be to the heavens.<br><p>Countless artistic images have been forged to attempt to descibe what that particular sensation of a place where you can look up and down at the same time.  From songs, to paintings and photographs and poetry and film - all describing a different path from the millions of lives we lead.  From babeling construction to gastronomical delites, sunbathing and masturbation - all our human pursuits captured in the artist's eye in an attempt to render the essence of life on the roof top.<br><br>
          <font size="1"><a href="2002_08_01_blog.html#80508662">posted at 12:49 AM</a></font>
     </blockquote>
     <p>

     
          <h4>Tuesday, August 13, 2002</h4>
     
     <blockquote>
 		  <a name="80183409"></a><br>
          John Sterns better hope he doesn't run into me in a dark alley 'cause only one of us will be walking out...<br><p>I'm a pretty dedicated mets fan - but even i with my acute fascination in the morbid can't watch them finish their season.  It seems at this point the only graceful end to the debacle that is the Mets 40th anniversary season would be a Players Union Strike that cripples the entire sport.<br><p>It's not simply the pain of loss as true Mets fans are immune to that pain.  We're all too familiar with their knack for snatching defeat from the jaws of victory - it's their defining characteristic - yet we stand by them because they're our team.  No, it's not the losing.  It's not the "what could have been", and it's not the 4 year old routine of being oh so close, yet never further away, it's not the endless jeering from the simian blowholes woshiping at the altar of greed manned by our cross-town counterparts, and it's not the squabbles and scandal of the embarassing buyout between owners Fred Willpon and Nelseon Doubleday.<br><p>No.  The misery comes from the fact that the answer to this riddle is oh so obvious yet not acted upon.  It's obvious now to everyone it seems except the met's front office.  When a team with as much talent and potential as the mets - with a roster chock full of perrenial all stars and future hall of famers - can't even play .500 baseball, then the problem is the not the players.  IT'S THE COACHING STAFF.  To be fair, steve phillips is a bit of a miracle worker, he did pull a coup this past winter in stocking the mets bench with talent and potential.  <br><p>But it was merely potential for manager bobby valentine to squander.  It's been 4 years now that this nitwit has poured his energies into defending mediocre performances rather than elevating his team's level of play by any means neccessary.  He has simply not been able to do a mangers job - WIN.  How many chances does he get?  <br><p>If Bobby V. is the Moe the Stooge of the Mets, then his Larry and Curly are batting coach John Sterns and Infield Coach Matt Galanti.  Who are these guys?  How does an infield with 3 GOLD GLOVE players have the MOST ERRORS in the league?  You think all of a sudden the entire infield just mysteriously lost all fundamental abilities by coincidence?  you think that the middle of their lineup - a bunch of guys with a collective .300 career average stopped hitting because they were 'adjusting'?  Isn't it the coaches job to lead them through that?<br><p>so... let's see some action Steve.  Let's dump the junk and get this show on the road already already.<br><br>
          <font size="1"><a href="2002_08_01_blog.html#80183409">posted at 9:27 AM</a></font>
     </blockquote>
     <p>

     
          <h4>Monday, August 05, 2002</h4>
     
     <blockquote>
 		  <a name="79852728"></a><br>
          On revision...<br><p>i like to edit things - to tweak, twist and temper things until they're just right.  Or until i run out of time, whichever comes first.  I have a perfectionist's compulsion to go back to the source and try to make it juuust a little bit more... right.  Not always better, but make whatever it is i'm comsumed with doing, just so.  Just the way i think it needs to be.<br><p>I had a drawing teacher who told me that no draft is ever complete without lots of eraser marks and scratches.  You should be able to see the mistakes because the mistakes meant that there was change and evolution; that there was growth.  If there weren't any mistakes then the work was staid and stagnant.  dead.   In his mind, drawing is like life, and life is an evolution.  To use the ever popular metaphor of "a journey", the journey of life follows a path that is marked by milestones of growth and learning.  If that path of life has no milestones, or mistakes, then you must not have gotten anywhere - you didn't learn anything.  The only way we learn is by challenging or changing what we know.  In drawing - that's marking a line representing what we see, examining it, and then changing it to be truer to what IS.  This is what we call a mistake, or a milestone.  It's a matter of learning what is. <br><p>I don't think my penchant for revising all that i do is always a growth process - usually it's just procrastination.  But that's ok i guess.  It is what it is, but there is a problem with it.   It's easy to fall into an infinite loop of editing.   Perpetually rehashing what is already "done enough".  For a while i've tried to balance this out with just "getting it done."  forge full steam ahead without looking back and let inspiration and the subconscious run its course.  Then when you DO look back you have a 'whole' to work with and examine.  a foundation to build from.<br><br>
          <font size="1"><a href="2002_08_01_blog.html#79852728">posted at 1:46 PM</a></font>
     </blockquote>
     <p>


